  "text": "The Android Activity lifecycle is implemented across four key Java source files in the AOSP framework:\n\n1. **Activity.java** (core/java/android/app/Activity.java): The base Activity class that defines the public lifecycle methods including onCreate(), onStart(), onResume(), onPause(), onStop(), and onDestroy(). This is the API surface that developers override to implement their application logic during different lifecycle stages.\n\n2. **ActivityThread.java** (core/java/android/app/ActivityThread.java): The main thread handler for an Android application process. This class receives lifecycle transition messages from the system and dispatches them to the appropriate Activity instances through a series of internal lifecycle callbacks. It extends ClientTransactionHandler and is responsible for processing server transactions that drive lifecycle state changes.\n\n3. **ActivityRecord.java** (services/core/java/com/android/server/wm/ActivityRecord.java): The server-side representation of a running Activity instance. This WindowToken subclass maintains the state of an Activity as seen by the WindowManagerService and ActivityTaskManagerService. It handles visibility transitions, window management, and acts as the server-side counterpart to the client-side Activity class.\n\n4. **ActivityTaskManagerService.java** (services/core/java/com/android/server/wm/ActivityTaskManagerService.java): The primary system service that manages activity stacks, tasks, and lifecycle transitions. This IActivityTaskManager.Stub implementation is responsible for enforcing lifecycle state transitions, managing the activity stack, and coordinating lifecycle changes with the WindowManagerService and other system services.\n\nThese four components work together to implement the Android Activity lifecycle: the system service (ActivityTaskManagerService) manages overall state transitions, the server-side representation (ActivityRecord) maintains state consistency, the main thread (ActivityThread) receives and processes lifecycle events, and the Activity class provides the API for application developers."
}

